{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868892/1930090301/0404.xml":{"full_text":"It Seems to Me\nHEWO\u00ae BROUN\nCALVIN COOLIDGE has begun to go the way of all\ncolumnists. He has started to wisecrack. I knew\nit had to happen eventually, but it has come much sooner\nthan I expected. I felt he could continue for another\nmonth or so with little pieces pointing out that the sun\nrises in the east and that unemployment is caused by peo\nple being out of work.\nHis first venture into the comic field is mild enough. Mr. Coolidge\ndid no more than write, in a column explaining that Frenchmen live in\nFrance, \u201cThey remembered the Marne.\u201d\nThis punning reference to our famous Spanish-American war slogan\nmight ndt definitely establish the fact Coolidge is out to ride with the\nhounds who bay and bay and bay. I\u2019m not saying he has become a\nsnappy paragrapher overnight. Such things take time. Walter Win\nchell wasn\u2019t made in a day.\nCoolidge and the Comic Muse.\nBUT it is a beginning. And once the move has been made momen\ntum gathers swiffly. Within a month I predict that Calvin Cool\nidge will be remembering paired Irishmen and repeating Ford jokes.\nEven an ex-president can\u2019t get a daily piece forever out of the United\nStates constitution and the Ten Commandments. The air grows rare\nfied when any one flies constantly for platitude.\nMark you, I am not blaming Mr. Coolidge in the least. Even to a\nserious writer like myself days come when the temptation to try a gag\n\u2014good or bad \u2014becomes irresistible. Calvin Coolidge is, among other\nthings, human. Naturally, it pleases him when cronies say, \u201cThat was\na fast one you pulled in your column today, Cal.\u201d\nDecorous approbation for noble sentiments expressed is well enough,\nbut every newspaperman needs at times more heady stuff. He craves\nthe swift exhilaration that comes from the laughter of the crowd.\nYet for this wine of stimulation he must pay the price. I hope Mr.\nCoolidge is embarking upon the career of a funny man with both eyes\nopen. Between us there is so much in common I hope he will under\nstand that all advice I may give is of the most friendly nature. Both\nof us are attempting the^fficult stunt of trying to combine campaign\ning and columns.\nIt is true that Mr. Coolidge is politically obscure at the moment.\nHe didn\u2019t get any nomination this year. Better luck next time, Cal.\nAnd lam sure there will be a next time. Though the memory of voters\nis short, some few of us still remember that Calvin Coolidge gave an ex\ncellent account of himself as a selectman in Northampton.\nThat Old Sim Dodger!\nHIS chance will come again, but I want to warn him about what the\nelectorate and the daily papers will say when next he enters the\npolitical arena. He will have to face the charge that he is, after all, a\ncomic columnist and that it is his business to get out a daily entertain\ning screed and leave more momentous things to the serious-minded who\nneither joke nor spin.\nThe rumor will gain currency that Mr. Coolidge has gone into poli\ntics simply to get publicity for the column he is running. There will be\na whispering campaign to the effect that he never goes to bed except\nby accident or invitation. Somebody will say politics is no place for a\ntrout fisherman. Particularly for a man who uses worms as bait. They\nwill rake up old photographs of Mr. Coolidge with a sap bucket. Mr.\nCoolidge attempting to ride a bucking bronco, Mr. Coolidge in a five\ngallon hat, and ask whether any person so undignified has a right to sit\nin solemn conclave with the selectmen of Northampton.\nMore than that, it may be roundly asserted that he is just running\nfor the exercise and that it would be a tragic disappointment to him\nif he won, sincb that might interfere with his newspaper job and his\nradio broadcasting. And, of course, his opponents will say, \u201cCal is a\nnice fellow, but why throw away your vote?\u201d\nNot Bad for a Beginner.\n1 TRUST Mr. Coolidge will have the hardihood to stand the gaff. It\nseems to me not unreasonable that a personage who was once the\nfirst gentleman of the land should have his fling at trying to be the 25th\nwit. \u201cRemember the Marne!\u201d is not bad at all\u2014not for a beginner.\nI\u2019ve heard worse than that pulled in the late hours at the Thanatopsis\nclub. Above all, Mr. Coolidge\u2019s little jest has in it no shade of impro\npriety. It\u2019s just good, clean fun.\nThere was, of course, one great Republican who managed to achieve\npolitical success in spite of the fact that some of his jokes were not for\nmixed company. But he ran before the days of suffrage. Emulation is\ndifficult. If Mr. Coolidge hears or invents any anecdotes having to do\nwith a farmer\u2019s wife and a traveling salesman I urge him to confine\nthe telling to such occasions on which he is whooping it up with the\nnewspaper boys. Stories like that are calculated to lose him votes.\nPolitics, like the theater, is a jealous and an enticing mistress. The\nofficeholder returns to his own platform. Not forever can the former\nselectman sit upon the sidelines chirping from time to time, \u201cHold \u2019em,\nHoover!\u201d He, too, will itch to raise a right hand against the evening\nsky and shout, \u201cFellow voters of Northampton, if elected I promise you\nthat\u201d-\u2014\nIt doesn\u2019t matter what he promises. The simple slogan of \u201cGet hot\nwith Calvin Coolidge!\u201d should sweep him back to power. He can shed\nthe mantle of the professional humorist without great difficulty. At\nsuch times as he wants t| say something excruciating let him just think\nof the present tariff and'grow sober-vlsaged upon the instant. Anyhow,\nwho says that there is no room for anything funny in politics? Isn\u2019t\nthe noble experiment still with us?\nAnd so I welcome a comrade in quest of his youth!\n8,000 VOTERS\nREGISTER FOR\nPRIMARY POLL\nNew registrations received by\nthe city election commission dur\ning the last two weeks total B,(MX),\nSenator Schultz, secretary, an\nnounced today.\nThe commission booths on the\nfirst floor of the city hall will con\ntinue to be open every night until\n9 to Friday night. Registration of\npersons who wish to vote in the\nprimary, Sept. 16, must be made by\nthat time.\nPersons who do not register must\nho sworn in af-.the election booth\nnd must present two witnesses.\nWIFE TELLS OF\nDEATH THREAT;\nGIVEN DIVORCE\nAfter Mrs. Belle King testified in\nher divorce ease against Milton\nKing. 661 Delaware ave., today\n\u2019*\u00abt he told her he would give her\n>t Jake Lingle got\u201d and related\nircumstances of several attacks\ncd by her to have been made\nher husband. Circuit Judge\nhn 0. Kleczka allowed her a de\nree.\nShe was also given $650 instead\nof alimony. Iler husband was\npresent at the hearing, but did not\ndeny any of the charges.\nThey were married Dec. 3, 1929,\nat Waukegan, and separated seven\nmonths letter.\nWIFE SAYS RICH\nMATE BEAT HER;\nSEEKS DIVORCE\nMichael Klamacki, reputed\nwealthy owner of south side real\nestate and a former shoe dealer, is\nmade defendant in a suit for di\nvorce begun in circuit court late yes\nterday by Mrs. Pearl Klamacki.\nShe says he is worth SIOO,OOO, and\nlists_ property including a building\nat 551 Mitchell st., which she values\nat SBO,OOO.\nHe beat her each day for the past\nfour months, she declares. They\nwere married in 1923, and have six\nchildren. She is 36 years old, and\nhe is 41.\nState Nurses to\nMeet Here Tuesday\nThe fourth and fifth districts of\nthe Wisconsin Nurses Assn, will\nmeet at 8 p. m. Tuesday at 88\nProspect ave.\nThe program will Include reports\nof the biennial nursing convention.\nStella Ackley \\vill discuss Nurs\ning Education: C. Jane Buechler\nwill talk on Private Duty Nursing\nand Clara B. Rue will talk on Pub\nlic Health Nursing.\nAt the Beaches\nTEMPERATURE OF WATER\nGordon 74\nLincoln 70\nSouth Shore 65\nMcKinley 64\nATTENDANCE YESTERDAY\nMcKinley 129\nSouth Shore 92\nGordon \u2014.431\nLincoln 70\n109,100 Children Back at School Here Today\nPUPILS 3,000\nMORE NUMEROUS\nTHAN IN PAST\n80,000 Enrolled in\nPublic Schools\nHere.\nThe business of going to school\nbegan in earnest today, with ap\nproximately 109,000 pupils enrolled\nin the various public, private and\nparochial schools throughout the\ncity.\nThis registration is estimated to\nbe about 3,000 in excess of the en\nrollment during for me r years,\nthough the exact numbers will not\nbe known until early tomorrow, aft\ner the reports of the 115 public in\nstitutions and the numerous private\nand religious schools are received at\nthe school administration building.\nImprovements Are Noted.\nExtensive improvements and ren\novations have been made in many of\nthe high and grade school buildings\nduring the summer months, with\nBoys\u2019 Technical High school, South\nDivision High and the Keefe Ave\nnue school enlarged to accommodate\nthe increasing number of registra\ntions.\nThe Blue Mound Junior High\nschool, on Fairview ave., between\nSixty-fifth and Sixty-sixth sts., is\nthe one entirely new building added\nto Milwaukee\u2019s schools. Pupils en\nrolled there formerly attended five\nschools in the neighborhood, includ\ning the Ludington and Blaine\nschools. They will be housed tem\nporarily in barracks.\nThe recent controversy as to who\nshould operate the Pleasant View\nand Garden Acres schools has been\nsettled and students living outside\nthe city limits are having their tui\ntion paid by the town of Wauwa\ntosa, as was done in former years.\nBurned School Opened.\nThose pupils, who, reluctant to\nreturn to school, rejoiced at the\nburning of the Vieau school last\nweek have found their joy short\nlived, as hurried repairs made it\npossible for the opening of the\nschool today, with the exception of\nthree rooms, which will be ready in\nabout two weeks, according to Mil\nton C. Potter, superintendent of\nschools.\nWhitefish Bay freshmen refused\nadmission in the Shorewood High\nschool since last year, entered their\nown high school in Whitefish Bay\ntoday, though no arrangements\nhave been made as yet for upper\nclassmen, who will continue their\nstudies at the Shorewood High\nschool. Facilities will be provided\nfor, third and fourth year classes\nas the building of the school pro\ngresses.\nEnrollments at West Milwaukee\nHigh school yesterday were so\nheavy it was necessary to transfer\nsome of the pupils to South Divi\nsion and Bay View High schools.\n24,000 in Catholic Schools.\nAccording to figures submitted to\ndate, 80,000 students began the new 7\nterm in the public schools today,\nwith 24,000 entered in the Catholic\nschools and approximately 5,000\nenrolled in Lutheran parochial and\nprivate institutions.\nThe faculty members in the pub\nlic schools total 2,407, although last\nminute additions may increase this\nnumber.\nTheT unemployment situation in\nMilwaukee is responsible for the re\nturn of many students who had\nplanned to drop school, but resumed\ntheir studies because of their in\nability to find work..\nChildren Now Love\nSchool, Says Potter\nThe First Day of School was the\nsubject of an address by Milton C.\nPotter, superintendent of Milwau\nkee public schools, at a Kiwanis\nclub luncheon at 12:05 p. m. today\nin the Milwaukee Athletic club.\n\u201cThis is the spring of the aca\ndemic year, and the first day of\nschool is May day,\u201d Potter said.\n\u201cThe academic year is a year of\ndelightful happy work, purposeful\nplay and enthusiastic activities.\n\u201cNo longer ^pes the boy \u2018creep\nunwillingly to school,\u201d as described\nin Shakespeare\u2019s As You Like It.\nThe school of today is filled with\ncolor and execution of desire on the\nchild\u2019s part.\n\u201cHowever great the teacher\u2019s\nskill, however, indefatigable her in\ndustry, none of this effort is per\nmitted to dull the child's sense of\nplay and initiative, and he no long\ner walks with lagging steps to\nschool.\u201d\nVocation School\nWill Open Monday\nAssuming that the Milwaukee\nVocational schools\u2019 opening corre\nsponded with that of the public\nschools, several hundred pupils ap\npeared to register today.\nThis school staff, although l busy\narranging programs for the coming\nsemester, enrolled all those who\ncame. The school reopens Monday.\nLast year 9.439 pupils enrolled\nthe first week. The maximum at\ntendance was approximately 13.000\nSuburban School\nEnrollment Rises\nSchool opened yesterday in six of\nthe seven suburbs of Milwaukee,\nand Whitefish Bay schools resumed\nsessions today.\nReports indicate that the enroll\nment this year will exceed that of\nlast year.\nA first year high school course Is\nbeing offered in Whitefish Bay for\nthe first time this year. In the\nnast the Shorewood high school has\ntaken tuition pupils from White\nfish Bay. Fox Point and the town\nof Milwaukee. i\n.THE MILWAUKEE LEADER. WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 3, 1930.\n/Wk\nni mul\nBiSl^\nThese two cars were prizes\nawarded in The Milwaukee Lead\ner\u2019s circulation drive. In the up\nper picture Mrs. Theodore Tiegs,\nCOLEMAN SEES\nMORE SUNSHINE,\nAND COOL WINDS\nMore sunshine and refreshingly\ncool north winds will mark the con\ntinuation of fair weather Milwau\nkee enjoyed yesterday, according to\nFrank H. Coleman, w\u2019eather ob\nserver.\nVariation of 10 degrees fr*m\nminimum to maximum temperatire\nwas noted yesterday. The lowet\ntemperature was 60 degrees and t\u00bbe\nhighest 70 degrees.\nThe minimum temperature tody\nw 7 as 60 degrees at 4a. m. and f 3\ndegrees at noon w 7 as the maximim.\nThe mercury will not rise mi?b\nover the 75-degree mark, accord\u2019ig\nto Coleman, and much coler\nweather is expected tonight.\nAugust Heat Uniform.\nAugust was as warm as jly,\naccording to the weather bureu\u2019s\nmonthly summary, issued toey.\nThe average temperature was 18\ndegrees which is exactly that a*r\naged in July.\nThe heat in August, howeir,\nv^as more uniform there being oiy\nfour days that the mercury soar?\nabove 90 degrees, while in Jul\nseven days recorded above 90.\nWannest Since 1900.\nThe last month was the warmesi\nAugust since 1900 when an average\ntemperature of 75 was registered,\nThree times since that, the aver\nages have been equal to that of the\n72.8 degree mark, which is 3J\nabove normal.\nRainfall is 1.46 inches, one incl\nof which fell on the last day of the\nmonth, is 1.2 inches below 7 the no:-\nmal rainfall and is 1.05 inches moB\nthan last fall w\u2019hich was one of tie\ndryest Augusts on record.\nStart Wrecking of\nMerrill Building\nRazing of the seven-story Mfr\nrill theater building was started o\nday.\nThe permit for the wrecking wis\nissued to the Cuyahogh Wreckhg\nCo., Cleveland, by Building Inspe\ntor Leon M. Gurda, late yesterday.\nThe estimated expense is $3,000.\nIt is believed that the S. 8\nKresge Co. will build a three-stcy\nstore and office building on tie\nsite.\nSCHOOL IEACHFR\nSTILL MISSING\nA two-day search failed to re-tai\nthe whereabouts of Vera Belle Pul,\n22 years old. Mason City, la., schol\nteacher, who disappeared Morfay\nwhile en route to Milwaukee Dm\nher home.\nShe was to have met ancher\nteacher. Miss Louella B. Cuiiss,\nNew Holstein. The two had planed\nto drive to Mount Vernon, N Y.,\nwhere they were to teach scool,\nMiss Curtiss told police.\nDetectives believe Miss Pai is\nsomewhere in Milwaukee. 8b is\nthe daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Fink\nPaul, Mason City. Her father issec\nretary of the Farmers\u2019 Mutual afe\nInsurance Co. there.\nDisappearance of William Vti\nrraf, 26 years old. 304 Eighth t.,\nvho was last seen Saturday, as\neported today to police.\nAWARDED IN LEADER DRIVE\n3y Leader Staff Photographer.\n1245 Fifty-fifth st., is on the left\nwth the Chevrolet coach which\nsle won. With her is Mrs. Her\nbert Daum. Mrs. Ida Bagemihl,\nBITTY HAISLER\nIN STH GRADE\nAT-TEN YEARS\nT^n-year-old Betty Haisler,\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. Ray Hais\nler, 871 Third st., took her place in\nthe eighth grade in the Island Ave\nnue school, among pupils three and\nfour years older than she.\nBetty has reached the eighth\ngrade by combining part of the first\nand second and the third and\nfourth grade work in single semes\nters, and by attending summer\nschool for two summers.\nMrs. Haisler is president of the\nLincoln High School Parent-Teach\ners\u2019 Assn.\nCOUNSEL FIGHTS\nPRESENT CIVIL\nSERVICE TESTS\nContinued objection was made to\nthe use of rhe word \u201ccolored\u201d in\nany respect in connection with the\n^a^ination for a social worker by\nA J?ferney George 11. De Reef in the\nase in which he appears for John\nS Bennings, colored taxpayer,\ngainst the county civil service\nommission.\nProceedings in the case today be\n\u00bbre Cricuit Judge John J. Gregory\nresulted in no action by the judge\nafter De Reef refused to sign a\nstipulation providing for the elimi\nnation of the word \u201ccolored\u201d from\nthe legal description of the newly\ncreated job of social worker.\nDe Reese objected to. the addi\ntional part of the stipulation, which\nprovided that work should be lim\nited to \u201ccolored persons.\u201d\n\u201cThis would still amount to a\ndiscrimination under the 14th\namendment to the United States\nconstitution, I fear,\u201d De Reef said.\n\u201cI refuse to sign any such stipu\nlation.\u201d\nDe Reef and his associate Attor\nney George W. Dorsey both object\nto the limiting of a civil service\nexamination to colored people only.\nThey are willing that a colored man\nor woman should be appointed to\nthe position, they say, but feel that\na dangerous precedent will be es\ntablished by discriminating as to\ncolor among the applicants for the\nexamination, which later may result\nin examinations being held in\nwhich colored people are barred.\nFreud, Famous for\nPsychoanalysis, Is\nNear Death at 74\nVIENNA. Austria Sigmund\nFreud, father of psychoanalysis, is\nslowly dying from cancer of the\ntongue and throat, it was learned\nTuesday. Doctors believe he will\nlive only a few months.\nThe disease, which began in the\nfore part of the tongue, has already\ncrept to the throat. When it\nreaches the larynx it will mean\ndeath, one physician said, adding\nthat an operation is made impossi\nble because of his advanced age. He\nis 74 years old. He became grave\nly ill three months ago.\nProf. Freud was unable to go to\nFrankfort to receive the annual\nGothe prize last week, and sent his\ndaughter to read his address. Al\nthoush he is not bedridden, it is\nsaid tie has givea up all woxX\n225 Williams st., below, was the\nwinner of the Oakland custom\nsedan, the fourth prize in the\ndrive.\nONE-MAN CARS\nOPPOSED FOR\nMITCHELL LINE\nLittle opposition was brought out\nat two hearings of the state rail\ncommission on petitions of The\nElectric Co., in the city hall today.\nOne hearing was on a rapid tran\nsit line to West Junction, southwest\nof the city, and the other, on plac\ning one-man street cars on the Hol\nton-Mitchell st. line.\nDelay One Hearing.\nThe hearing on the extension of\nthe rapid transit line was continued\nto 10:30 a. m. Wednesday at the\nrequest of representatives of the\ntown of Greenfield, who believe that\npersons living along the proposed\nline will express opposition.\nAid. Robert J. Landowski, non\npartisan, 13th ward, voiced the only\nopposition made to the one-man\nstreet car.\nHe said that the North Side Civic\nAssn, is opposed to it, and also\nmany workmen who .ire afraid they\nwould be late for work as the result\nof retarded service.\nOther aidermen whose wards ad\njoin the line expressed no opposi\ntion. v\nRequest Few Stops.\nR. H. Pinkley, vice president of\nthe company, proposed that the new\nrapid transit line be operated on\nthe basis of one stop for every four\nblocks. This service would permit\noperation of the ears over an eight\nmile stretch In 15 minutes.\nHe proposed a fare rate of 10\ncents from the Public Service build\ning to Eighty-fourth ave., and 15\ncents to West Junction. No trans\nfers would be given on other lines,\nand commutation tickets would be\nsold for $1.15 to Eighty-fourth ave.,\nfor a week, and $1.50 to West\nJunction.\nOpposition from the town of\nGreenfield will come over the pro\nposed fare schedule, it is believed.\nPROBE ADVISED\nIN SCHOOL SITE\nLAND DEALINGS\nFavoring an investigation of ru\nmors that 10 members of the school\nadministration office have pur\nchased real estate in the vicinity of\nproposed school sites. Director Har\nry V. Meissner placed the matter\nbefore the school board last night.\nA separate legal department for\nthe schools was suggested by Direc\ntor Waldemar Wehe. Roth resolu\ntions were placed before commit\ntees.\nA resolution asking that parents\nwhose children sustained injuries\non school playgrounds be compen\nsated was referred to the legisla\ntive committee.\nNew methods of textbook selec\ntion were asked by Director Loyal\nDurand, who advised that a special\ncommittee be provided for the pur\npose.\nFormal charges against Mrs.\nElizabeth Barr, educational depart\nment employe suspended for strik\ning a fellow stenographer, are to\nbe drawn by the city attorney in\naccordance with the decision of the\nboard, which will also make an in\nluiiy to determine the resDonsibil-\nWOMEN DESIRE\nRETURN OF OLD\nCORNER SALOON\n\u201cThe corner saloon,\u201d which wom\nen used to decry in theii tight for\nprohibition, is now spoken of lov\ningly by women in their fight\nagainst prohibition.\n\u201cIf we could only do away with\nthis evil,\u201d they used to say.\n\u201cIf we could only have visualized\nhow\u2019 much worse the mushroom\ngrowth which has sprung up in\ntheir absence would be,\u201d they now\nsay of the speakeasy, successor to\nthe saloon.\nIn room 318 of the Martin hotel,\na large table is piled high with\npamphlets, little and big, each\narguing the purposes and goal for\nwhich the Women\u2019s Organization\nfor* National Prohibition -Reform\nhas been organized within the last\nfew months.\nMrs. Bowler, Organizer.\nMrs. Gertrude Bowler, Sheboy\ngan, former national Democratic\ncommittee woman for \u2019Wisconsin, is\n\u2019Wisconsin\u2019s organizer in the new\u2019\nmovement, which is a non-political\nassociation.\nIt is rapidly recruiting women\nfrom all parties wjiose one idea is\nto get rid of the 18th amendment.\nMrs. Celia Keegan, wife of a new\nly appointed moving picture chain\nhead here, adds the eastern touch\nto proceedings. Pretty, and blond,\nand extremely energetic, Mrs. Kee\ngan talks New York \u2014especially\nHeywood Broun, Milwaukee Leader\ncolumnist and at preStent the So\ncialist candidate for congress from\na New York city district.\n\u201cThere\u2019s nobody like Broun,\u201d she\nexclaimed, launching into praise of\nthe words he uses and the ideas he\napplies them to, in his daily col\numn, It Seems To Me.\n\u201cEver since Massachusetts\nstained itself with the irradicable\nblot of executing Sacco and Van\nzetti, I have admired Broun\u2019s stand\non this and other similar national\ndisgraces,\u201d she declared.\nShe aded, whimsically, \u201cBroun is\nin favor of repeal, too.\u201d\nMrs. Bowler told of the things\nshe sees and hears of these days of\nprohibition that isn\u2019t prohibiting.\nOf gasoline stations which sell\nnothing but liquor, as related to\nher by a girl whose mother was\nafraid to send the child to her own\nstate university; 10-year-old chil\ndren peddling booze and declaring\nthey will be drawn and quartered\nbefore they will reveal their\nbosses; five speakeasies where one\nsaloon used to be.\nState Advisory Council.\nFrom room 318 comes this list of\nwomen whose names head Wiscon\nsin\u2019s membership as its advisory\ncouncil:\nMrs. Allan J. Roberts, Milwau\nkee.\nMrs. C. B. Whitnal, Milwaukee.\nMrs. John Mariner, Milwaukee.\nMrs. James Mehan, Milwaukee.\nMrs. Samuel Olson, Milwaukee.\nMrs. Paul Phillipson, Milwaukee.\nMrs. Arthur Telin, Milwaukee.\nMrs. Henry Brice, Milwaukee.\nMrs. Charles Borden, Milwaukee.\nMrs. Melvin Ladd, Milwaukee.\nMrs. A. J. Vits. Manitowoc.\nMrs. Hobart Johnson, Madison.\nMrs. John Hoberg, Green Bay.\nMrs. Henry Fellenz, Fond du\nLac.\nMrs. J. M. Dowd, Fond du Lac.\nMrs. William Castle, Oshkosh.\nMrs. H. C. Miller, Racine.\nSAYS MONOPOLY\nIS PURPOSE OF\n*C 0 0 PERATIVE'\nThe whole scheme in the creation\nof the Building Material co-opera\ntive was to maintain an unlawful\nmonopoly in the purchase and sale\nof lime, cement, plaster, lath, cop\ning and similar materials, It was\ncharged today in an answer filed\nby S. Rauwerdink and Co. to a\nsuit brought by the co-operative as\nsociation for the collection of a\npast due note for $4,000.\n27 Dealers Are Members.\nTo illustrate how the alleged\nmonopoly is maintained, tfee answer\nstates that 27 out of 31 Milwaukee\ndealers in the products mentioned\nare members of the co-operative;\nthat the co-operative fixes all\nprices, dictates the manner of sale\nand distribution by its members,\nattempts to compel manufacturers\nto sell only to members and compels\nall members ro account for all sales.\nSome contractors are described by\nthe co-operative as \u201clegitimate\"\nand pay 15 per cent less for mate\nrials than \u201cillegitimate\u201d contractors.\nSays No Vahit Received.\nNo value was received for the\n$4,000 note, the answer also sets\nup, and the co-operative, in attempt\ning to collect on the note, is acting\nas a collection agency for the dealer\nwho made the sale, although it is\nnot licensed as a collection agency,\nthe answer charges.\nThe answer also describes how all\norders among the 27 members are\ncleared through the co-operative\nwhich gets 2 per cent for its serv\nice.\nAlimony Payments\nShow Upward Trend;\nYear's Record Set\nA return of prosperity in the\nranks of the alimony club is seen in\na sharp upward climb in alimony\npayments made yesterday, accord\ning to Circuit Court Clerk C. C.\nMaas. Yesterday 200 former hus\nbands paid over $0,500 to the clerk,\nmaking the day a record breaker\nfor the year.\nity for the fire in Vieau school,\nWalker and Greenbush sts.\nWalter E. Rilling, an instructor\n..t West Division High school, was\nippointed an assistant in the su-\nDerintendent's office.\nFEES ADVISED\nFOR WITNESSES\nOF FIRE BOARD\nRecommendation that witnesses\nsubpoenaed by the police and fire\ncommission at trials of department\nmembers be paid witness fees, was\nmade by the common council's fi\nnance committee at its meeting\nsince the aldermanic vacation late\nyesterday.\nIt was pointed out by Elmer\nGroth, assistant city, attorney, that\nthe witnesses who fail to answer a\nsubpoena cannot be charged with\ncontempt unless fees are paid.\nThe committee approved of tak\ning $25 from the contingent fund\nfor the fees. Nearly all business\nbefore both the finance committee\nand the public utilities and health\ncommittee was laid over for two\nweeks.\nAid. Carl P. Dietz, Socialist, 10th\nward, indicated that he would intro\nduce a resolution requiring an ac\ncounting for convention trips taken\nat the expense of the city by vari\nous city officials.\nIt was recommended that five\nhealth department representatives\nbe authorized to attend the Amer\nican Public Health Assn, conven\ntion at Fort Worth, Tex., next\nmonth.\nCHURCH'S HEAD\nOPENS SUIT TO\nKEEP HIS POST\nSuit was started in circuit court\ntoday by Herman C. Mueller, who\nwas elected president of the Pro\ngressive Spiritualist church, Thir\nteenth and Walnut sts., last De\ncember, for a permanent injunction\nrestraining officers elected in May\nfrom acting as officers, and re\nstraining them from holding any\nmeetings pertaining to the affairs\nof the church.\nAfter Mueller was elected in De\ncember, certain members of the\nchurch formed a secret agreement\nto oust him, he claims.\nAt the May business meeting it\nwas voted to change the constitu\ntion of the church and make the\nelection in May instead of Decem\nber. New officers were elected.\nClaims Election Void.\nMueller, represented by Attor\nneys Brennan, Lucas and McDon\nough, claims that the amendment\nto the constitution at the May meet\ning was not according to the consti\ntution and by-laws and therefore\nthe election held under that amend\nment is void, and Mr. Mueller is\nstill legally the president of the\norganization.\nNine of the 10 defendants named\nby Mueller are officers and trus\ntees elected at the May meeting.\nThey are:\nPresident, William H. Klein.\nSecretary, Mrs. E. M. Schultz.\nTreasurer, C. A. Bradley.\nFirst vice president, Mrs. Eline\nAndree.\nSecond vice president, Alfred\nRaduechel.\nTrustees,' Josephine Jacob, Har\nry C. Bradley, Estelle Chapman\nand Ortenze Glaser.\nGets Temporary Injunction.\nFrank A. Schultz, elected second\nvice president in December, is the\n10th defendant in the action.\nA temporary injunction restrain\ning the defendants from interfer\ning with Mueller\u2019s rights as presi\ndent was signed by Martin F. Bien\nski. court commissioner, yesterday.\nHearing on the question of the\npermanent injunction will lie held\nSaturday before Circuit Judge Otto\nM. Breidenbach.\nGovernor to See\nAll Quiet Monday\nMonday night has been set aside\nas governor\u2019s night at the Alham\nbra theater when the state\u2019s chief,\nexecutive will attend a special per\nformance of All Quiet on the West\nern Front, as the guest of the man\nagement.\nGov. Walter J. Kohler accepted\nthe invitation out of compliment to\nCarl Laemmle, Wisconsin\u2019s own\nmotion picture producer, and in def\nerence to his mightiest film achieve\nment.\nThe governor will speak from the\nstage at 8 p. m.\nHold Ex-Deputy on\nSerious Charges\nFrank Navatril, 4033 Twenty\nninth st., a former deputy sheriff,\nwas arrested yesterday at Port\nWashington on serious charges in\nvolving a young girl.\nNavatril is accused of having\nmistreated the child at a picnic at\nCedarburg Sunday.\nHe denied the charges and was\nreleased on SI,OOO bail. He will ap\npear in Port Washington for pre\nliminary hearing Monday.\nBARE TEACHER\nOUSTER HERE\nl^liss Lillian Hunsicker, for many\nyears head of the educational re\nsearch department, Milwaukee State\nTeacher\u2019s college, will terminate her\nconnections with the school Feb. 1,\naccording to a statement by Presi\ndent Frank E. Baker, today.\nMiss Hunsicker, however, dis\nclaimed any knowledge of her sever\nance of connections with the school,\nbut Baker insisted she will not be\na member of the faculty after\nFeb. 1.\nClarence R. Falk, Falk corpora\ntion. a member of the board of re\ngents. said there was some discus\nsion that there was no room at the\ncollege for Miss Hunsicker.\nInsubordination is cited as the\nreason for the administration's de\ncision to let Miss Hunsicker go.\nPage Two","height":"28395","width":"21108"}}
